{
  "doc_id": "28217",
  "text": "Recently, the inbred isogenic offspring of a C57Bl/6J mouse crossed with a s129/SvlmJ mouse (a strain commonly used to create mice with targeted mutations) was shown to develop obesity, insulin resistance, hypoadiponectinemia, adipose tissue inflammation, dyslipidemia, NAFL followed by progressive NASH and fibrosis and HCC with cell signaling, transcriptomic and lipidomic changes similar to humans with NASH [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Similarly, a model in which animals are administered a Western diet with weekly CCl 4, a hepatotoxin to amplify injury and fibrosis, also appears to closely resemble human NASH [CITATION_3] . Both of these models replicate the progressive stages of NAFLD from steatosis alone (NAFL) through NASH to cirrhosis and hepatocellular carcinoma without the addition of a carcinogen (for example, diethylnitrosamine). Although other animal species, ranging from zebrafish [CITATION_4] and fruit flies [CITATION_5] to the Ossabaw pig [CITATION_6] , have also been studied with respect to NASH, the translatability of results from these models (for example, zebrafish) to humans and logistical difficulties (for example, pig models) limit their utility.",
